# =============================================================================
# cursor ↦ lista — materialize a cursor into a list
# =============================================================================
#
# What this example teaches:
#   • cursor ↦ lista — eagerly materialize all elements from a cursor
#   • Two-step setup: lista → cursor (seed), then cursor → lista (collect)
#
# Syntaxes used:
#   • ↦ (conversion operator) — lines 10, 11
#   • incipit (entry point) — line 9
#   • fixum (immutable binding) — lines 10, 11
#
# Alternate approaches (not shown):
#   • itera ex cursor — lazy iteration without materializing; prefer when you only need one pass

# Anti-patterns (avoid these):
#   • itera ex cursor multiple times — cursors are single-pass; convert to lista for reuse
#   • lista ∷ cursor — static ascription cannot create a cursor; use ↦

# Pitfalls:
#   • Cursor is consumed by conversion — cannot iterate after ↦ lista
#   • Large cursors allocate full memory; prefer streaming iteration for big data

# Learning path:
#   Before: see cursor/ and lista/ exempla (Stage 6 types)
#   After:  see cat/src/main.fab (cursor-based file iteration with itera ex)

# Stage: Phase-1 model, both backends
# Backend: Rust ✓, wasm-text ✓
# =============================================================================
incipit {
    fixum cursor<numerus> c ← [1, 2, 3] ↦ cursor<numerus>
    fixum _ r ← c ↦ lista<numerus>
}
